The oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) efficiency of direct methanol fuel cell (DMFC) is of great significance. In this work, MnO2 supported on CeO2-QDs (CeO2-QDs@MnO2) and CeO2-QDs supported on MnO2 (MnO2@CeO2-QDs) composite with different loading method were synthesized to investigate the role of CeO2 for ORR, according to the excellent oxygen adsorption and oxygen ion conductivity of CeO2 quantum dots (CeO2-QDs). A passive DMFC was assembled by CeO2-QDs@MnO2 or MnO2@CeO2-QDs as cathodic catalyst and PtRu/C as anodic catalyst. The maximum power densities for CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs-based DMFCs were 9.4 and 7.8 mW·cm−2, while 8.5 and 7.0 mW·cm−2 for air-breathing DMFCs, respectively. CeO2-QDs@MnO2 showed a more superior ORR activity and stability in the high discharge currents especially for air-breathing DMFCs. The temporary storage and timely replenishment mechanism of oxygen in CeO2-QDs@MnO2 catalyst could significantly enhance the ORR efficiency at cathode. This work developed a new thought about the loading method of CeO2 on the ORR catalytic activity for CeO2/MnO2 catalysts. Graphical Abstract ga1 Keywords Passive direct methanol fuel cell Cathode catalyst Oxygen adsorption capacity MnO2 1 lntroduction Direct methanol fuel cells (DMFCs) can directly convert chemical energy into electrical energy as a neoteric power generation device for the high energy density, non-pollution, simple construction, quick startup and environmental friendliness [1–3]. DMFCs are classified into active and passive DMFCs according to the type of reactant supplied system. The active DMFCs should operate with the usage of external accessory devices for oxygen and methanol supplying. For comparison, the passive DMFCs worked without using the external accessory equipments, which were more desirable for practical application [4–6]. Recently, air-breathing DMFCs as a novel type of passive DMFCs have aroused great interests and application prospect, which assembled by passive fuel supply at the anode and air natural convection or diffusion at the cathode. However, their output performance especially for oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) activity at the cathode and high cost were unsatisfactory and still a serious issue [7,8]. Pt and Pt-based alloys are the most representative cathode catalysts for ORR, but the high cost and poor stability impede their commercial applications [9]. In this regard, non-precious metal ORR electrocatalysts such as metal alloys [10], M/N/C (M=Fe, Co etc.) [11,12] and transition metal compounds [13] have been developed as promising catalysts to improve the stability of cathode. Their outstanding ORR activities based on a three-electrode structure were even comparable to Pt/C catalyst [14]. Recently, transition-metal oxides, especially Mn-based oxides were reported as the most arresting cathodic catalysts in alkaline environment because of their geological abundance and considerable activity [15]. Despite of the superiorities mentioned above, there still existed some inherent defects including inferior electronic conductivity and oxygen adsorption capacity. Some efforts had attempted to alleviate these problems via compositing with conductive carbon matrix [16,17], designing mesoporous structure [18] and introducing oxygen vacancies [19]. However, the inferior oxygen adsorption and transfer capacity was remain restricted the cathodic performance, especially for the passive DMFCs operated in a higher current densities. The concentration polarization of oxygen would become a limiting factor on the cathode, but the above methods have finite effect on oxygen mass transfer. At present, some oxides with abundant oxygen vacancies (TiO2, Fe2O3 and CeO2) demonstrated as additive catalyst to enhance electrochemical activity in the field of energy and catalysis [20–22]. For example, CeO2 has attracted particularly attractive ascribe to its unique oxygen-storage capability and oxygen ion conductivity ability [23–25]. And when compositing CeO2 with the inferior oxygen-storage ability catalysts, such as MnO2, would greatly alleviate its concentration polarization of oxygen. Inspired by this idea, MnxCe1−xO2 solid solutions demonstrated many applications in the selective catalysis for volatile organic compounds [26] and toxic gases (such as CO, CH4 and NO) [27]. In addition, CeO2/MnO2 composites were also reported to enhance the oxygen adsorption capacity of MnO2 [28,29]. CeO2 was beneficial to convert the molecular oxygen to reactive oxygen species and improve their oxygen adsorption capacity. Moreover, the heterogeneous interfaces in CeO2/MnO2 composites could also improve their electrical conductivity [28]. In order to significantly increase the catalytic effect, CeO2 quantum dots (CeO2-QDs, <10 nm) was applied in some studies [24]. CeO2-QDs exhibited superior oxygen storage and adsorption capacity owing to its small size and high surface effects. In fact, some researchers have studied the catalytic effect of CeO2, but CeO2 was usually supported on the surface of MnO2, which resulted in the reduction of effective catalytic active sites on the MnO2 surface. For example, Cao [30] and Kim [31] loaded CeO2-QDs on the MnO2 matrix to obtain higher catalytic activity and reaction efficiency. Therefore, the loading method of CeO2 would affect the catalytic activity of CeO2/MnO2 [32,33]. In this study, two composites of CeO2-QDs@MnO2 (MnO2 supported on CeO2-QDs) and MnO2@CeO2-QDs (CeO2-QDs supported on MnO2) with different loading method were synthesized to investigate the role of CeO2 on the ORR activity. And then CeO2-QDs@MnO2 or MnO2@CeO2-QDs was used as cathode catalyst, PtRu/C as the anode catalyst, and PFM as electrolyte membrane to assemble the passive and air-breathing DMFCs. The results in this work indicated that CeO2-QDs@MnO2 showed the superior ORR activity and stability in the high discharge currents. This work developed a new thought about the loading method of CeO2 on the ORR catalytic activity for CeO2/MnO2 heterostructured catalysts. 2 Experimental section 2.1 Material preparation All reagents used in this experiment were of analytical grade by Sinopharm Chemical Reagent Co. Ltd. The 60 wt% PtRu/C and 20% Pt/C was supplied by Johnson Matthey (UK). The polymer fiber membrane (PFM) was purchased from Nippon Kodoshi Corporation, Japan. The Nafion NRE-211 membrane was purchased from Dupont Corporation, USA. 2.1.1 Preparation of CeO2-QDs CeO2-QDs was synthesized by the sol-gel method. Firstly, 0.15 mol Ce(NO)3 .6H2O and ammonium hydroxide were dissolved in deionized water with magnetic stirring until pH was 8.5. Subsequently, the precipitation product was washed with deionized water until the solution was neutral. Transfer the solution into the water bath heated at 60 °C and add dilute nitric acid to make the pH was 1.4. Then, 7.5 mol oleic acid was added and stirred for 2 h. Finally, after 12 h standing time and separating the aqueous phase, CeO2-QDs was obtained. 2.1.2 Preparation of CeO2-QDs@MnO2 Firstly, a certain amount of CeO2-QDs powder was dispersed into 80 mL mixed solution including manganese carbonate, nitric acid, and urea. After stirring at 60 °C for 2 h, 5 mg chelating agent consisting of citric acid and glycerin was added into the mixture. Subsequently, after drying at 80 °C, the precipitate was calcined in air at 500 °C for 4 h to obtain CeO2-QDs@MnO2 composite. The detailed synthesis procedure was shown in Scheme 1a. 2.1.3 Preparation of MnO2 Manganese sulfate and potassium permanganate were dissolved in deionized water at a molar ratio of 1:1. Then, the concentrated nitric acid was slowly added into the mixture until pH bellowed 7. After stirring for 30 min, the suspension was transferred to the Teflon hydrothermal reaction kettle and kept at 100 °C for 24 h. Finally, centrifuged and washed the precipitate by deionized water, and then dried at 80 °C to obtain MnO2 nanorods. 2.1.4 Preparation of MnO2@CeO2-QDs MnO2@CeO2-QDs was synthesized by the sol-gel method. Firstly, a certain amount of MnO2, 0.15 mol Ce(NO)3 .6H2O and ammonium hydroxide were dissolved in deionized water with magnetic stirring until pH was 8.5. Subsequently, the precipitation product was washed with deionized water until the solution was neutral. Transfer the solution into the water bath heated at 60 °C and add dilute nitric acid to make the pH was 1.4. Then, 7.5 mol oleic acid was added and stirred for 2 h. Finally, after 12 h standing time and separating the aqueous phase, MnO2@CeO2-QDs composite was obtained. The detailed synthesis procedure was shown in Scheme 1b. 2.2 Material characterization The microstructures of the as-prepared samples were analyzed by X-ray diffractometer (XRD, D/Max 2200 PC, Japan) and transmission electron microscopy (TEM, FEI company Tecnai G2 F20, USA). The morphologies were observed by field-emission scanning electron microscopy (FESEM, Hitachi S-4800, Japan). The specific Brunauer-Emmett-Teller (BET) surface area was tested by ASAP 2460 (Micromeritics Instrument Corporation, USA). X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) measurement (VG Thermo ESCALAB 250 spectrometer) was employed for analyze the surface chemical compositions. The quantitative analysis of metal elements was analyzed by ICP-AES (Inductively Coupled Plasma-Atomic Emission Spectrometry, THEM, USA). 2.3 Electrochemical measurements Electrochemical measurements were conducted on CHI 660E (Chenhua Instruments, China) electrochemical station using Pt-net and Hg/HgO electrode as the counter electrode and the reference electrode, respectively. The working electrode was prepared as follows: Firstly, CeO2-QDs, MnO2, CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2 @CeO2-QDs were respectively applied as catalysts, and there specific metal loading was tested by ICP-AES shown in Table S1. The comparison cathode used 5 mg Pt/C and 5 mg Nafion solution (5%). 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Structure and morphology The XRD patterns of CeO2-QDs and CeO2-QDs@MnO2 were shown in Fig. 1a. CeO2-QDs were prepared as the precursor of CeO2-QDs@MnO2 composite. The diffraction pattern for pure CeO2-QDs showed four sharp peaks at 28.54°, 33.08°, 47.47° and 56.33°, which were assigned to (1 1 1), (2 0 0), (2 2 0) and (3 1 1) crystalline facets of cubic fluorite structured CeO2 (JCPDS card No. 34–0394). As for the diffraction peaks of CeO2-QDs@MnO2, MnO2 (JCPDS card No. 44–0141) and CeO2 (JCPDS card No. 34–0394) were detected, signifying that CeO2-QDs@MnO2 was composited of CeO2 and MnO2. In Fig. 1b, the XRD pattern of pure MnO2, which used as the precursor of MnO2@CeO2-QDs, matched well with the standard MnO2 (JCPS card No. 44–0141). MnO2@CeO2-QDs was also in good agreement with the standard MnO2 (JCPDS card No. 44–0141) and CeO2 (JCPDS card No. 34–0394). No obvious impurity peak appeared. CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs indicated the similar phase composition. The x-ray diffraction pattern of CeO2-QDs@MnO2 especially for the CeO2 phase was very intense, in comparison with that of MnO2@CeO2-QDs. That was because in the synthesized procedure of CeO2-QDs@MnO2, the synthesized CeO2-QDs was calcined at 500 ℃ which resulted in the high crystallinity of CeO2 than the other sample. The surface morphologies of CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs samples were studied by SEM, as shown in Fig. S1. CeO2-QDs@MnO2 was assembled by numerous nanoparticles. MnO2@CeO2-QDs was composited of nanorods and numerous nanoparticles. Further microstructures of the composites were studied by TEM shown in Fig. 2. Fig. 2(a–b) presented the morphology of pure CeO2-QDs with the diameter of 5–7 nm. The interplanar spacing of 0.312 and 0.191 nm were in accord with (1 1 1) and (2 2 0) plane. The microstructure of CeO2-QDs@MnO2 was shown in Fig. 2(c–d). The apparent interplanar distance of 0.239, 0.244 and 0.309 nm were in consistent with (2 3 9), (4 0 0) and (3 1 0) planes of MnO2, respectively. And the other interplanar distances of 0.312 and 0.270 nm, respectively pointing to the (1 1 1) and (2 0 0) planes of CeO2. CeO2-QDs particles were wrapped in MnO2. Fig. 3(a–b) showed the TEM images of MnO2, which was the as the precursor of MnO2@CeO2-QDs composite. MnO2 presented nanorods structure with a diameter of 10 nm and a length of about 20 nm. The interplanar spacings of 0.244, 0.31 and 0.475 nm were in accord with (0 0 6), (3 1 0) and (1 0 1) planes of MnO2. In Fig. 3(c–d), MnO2 @CeO2-QDs composite was composed of MnO2 nanorods and CeO2 nanoparticles. CeO2 nanoparticles with the diameter of about 7 nm uniformly loaded on the surface of MnO2 nanorods. The interplanar distance of 0.19 and 0.45 nm, respectively matched (2 2 0) plane for CeO2 and (1 0 1) plane for MnO2. According to the above analysis, CeO2 as the additive catalyst in CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs indicated the different loading method in accord with Scheme 1. The surface chemical composition and oxidation states of CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs were investigated by XPS. As shown in Fig. 4a, the survey spectra of the above samples identified the presence of Mn, Ce, O elements. Fig. 4(b–d) showed the high resolution spectra of Mn 2p, Ce 3d and O 1s. Mn 2p could be divided into three peaks at 641.2641.99 eV, 642.53643.26 eV and 644.8645.1 eV, which were ascribed to Mn2+, Mn3+ and Mn4+, respectively [37,38]. The high-resolution spectrum for Ce 3d was classified into two spin splitting orbits of Ce 3d5/2 and Ce 3d3/2. The two spin splitting orbits can be fitted into six peaks of V, V2, V3, U, U2 and U3 peaks for Ce4+, while V1 and U1 can be fitted for Ce3+. The corresponding O 1s spectra contributed to three peaks at 530.58, 528.89 and 526.46 eV, respectively, corresponding to Osurf, Oads and Olat [13]. Osurf represents the surface adsorbed oxygen with weakly bonding oxygen species, while Olat is labeled as the lattice oxide oxygen. Oads shows the existence of oxygen vacancies on the surface of the samples. Oxygen vacancies acts as oxygen adsorption sites and can be greatly promoted the oxygen and electron transfer rate for ORR. Table 1 listed the surface concentrations of O, Ce and Mn species in the two composites. The contents of Oads in CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2 @CeO2-QDs were estimated to be 44.09% and 78.55%. In MnO2@CeO2-QDs composite, CeO2 was supported on the surface of MnO2 which resulted in larger amounts of oxygen vacancies. Cerium cation in CeO2 could easily change its oxidation state from Ce4+ to Ce3+ by the equation of C e O 2 ↔ C e O 2 − x + x 2 O 2 , according to the surrounding environment and accompany with the formation of oxygen vacancies. For CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2 @CeO2-QDs, the value for Ce3+/(Ce4++Ce3+) were 0.20 and 0.13, respectively, which demonstrated more oxygen vacancies and unsaturated chemical bonds in CeO2-QDs@MnO2. As depicted in Table 1, the atom ratio of Mn4+/ (Mn4+ + Mn3+ + Mn2+) in CeO2-QDs@MnO2 was calculated to be 0.24, which was lower than that of MnO2@CeO2-QDs. It was reported that lower valent manganese species demonstrated high catalytic activity in reduction reaction, and the transformation from Mn4+ to Mn3+ or Mn2+ could also form oxygen vacancies [9]. Furthermore, the microstructure of heterogeneous interface should be Ce1−xMnxO2 substitutional solid solution [26,27]. Ce4+ could be displaced with Mn3+ by the equation of C e 4 + + O 2 - → Mn 3 + + V o ∞ with the concomitant formation of oxygen vacancies [39]. Hence, the coupling influence of the relative lower concentration of Mn4+ and higher oxygen vacancy could improve the intrinsic activity. 3.2 Oxygen reduction reaction activity The oxygen reduction activity was evaluated by cyclic voltammogram (CV) and liner sweep voltammogram (LSV) measurements with the rotating ring-disk electrode (RRDE). The CV curves of CeO2, MnO2, CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs modified glass carbon electrodes were shown in Fig. 5a, which carried out in 1 mol KOH electrolyte saturated with O2 or N2. In N2-saturated electrolyte, the CV curves for each catalyst didn't reveal obvious oxidation or reduction peaks. All the catalysts indicated a well-defined cathodic peak, confirming their ORR activity. To evaluate the intrinsic catalytic activity between MnO2@CeO2-QDs and CeO2-QDs@MnO2, the CV curve was normalized with its corresponding BET surface area to exclude the influence of specific surface area for each catalyst. Fig. S2 showed the nitrogen adsorption-desorption curves and pore size distribution. The BET surface areas for MnO2@CeO2-QDs and CeO2-QDs@MnO2 were 41.774 and 48.479 m2·g−1, respectively. The current density was capacitive corrected by deducting the measured current density in N2 from that obtained in O2. As shown in Fig. 5b, the onset potential (Eonset) for MnO2@CeO2-QDs in CV curves were 0.84 V (vs. RHE). And a more positive Eonset of 0.91 V (vs. RHE) and higher current density was shown by CeO2-QDs@MnO2, illustrating its superior ORR intrinsic catalytic activity than MnO2@CeO2-QDs. The LSV curves at various rotating speeds were carried out in O2-saturated 1 mol KOH solution for CeO2-QDs, MnO2, MnO2@CeO2-QDs and CeO2-QDs@MnO2, as shown in Fig. 6(a–d). The currents were capacitive corrected by deducting the background tested in N2-saturated electrolyte. The obtained LSV curves demonstrated the directly proportional relationship between the current density and the rotation rate, suggesting they were active for ORR. The corresponding Kouetecky-Levich (K-L) plots for each catalyst at different potential were illustrated in the inset. Fig. 6e presented the LSV curves for each catalyst at 1600 rpm, while the commercial Pt/C catalysts was also provided for comparison. The Ehalf-wave value of Pt/C at 1.92 mA·cm−2 was found to be 0.75 V vs. RHE, whereas the MnO2@CeO2-QDs and CeO2-QDs@MnO2 catalyst exhibited an Ehalf-wave value of 0.71 and 0.70 V vs. RHE. Based on the Levich equation and above LSV results, the electron transfer number (n) and the H2O2 percentage (X H2O2 ) could be obtained in Eq. (2) and Eq. (3). The calculated n was 2.64, 3.28, 3.79, 3.94 and 3.99 for CeO2, MnO2,MnO2@CeO2-QDs, CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and Pt/C, while the corresponding X H2O2 were 36%, 68%, 10.5%, 3% and 2.7%, respectively. These results demonstrated that ORR on CeO2-QDs@MnO2 followed a near four-electron reaction pathway and less H2O2 yielded, confirming its high ORR activity than MnO2@CeO2-QDs. 3.3 DMFCs performance To evaluate the passive DMFCs performance, CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs were used as cathode catalyst, while PtRu/C was applied as the anode catalyst. The microstructure of cathode was shown in Fig. S3a, which was composed of a gas diffusion layer, a current collector and a catalyst layer. Fig. S3b is the microstructure of PFM used as electrolyte membrane. Fig. 7a showed the polarization and power density curves for CeO2-QDs@MnO2-based passive DMFCs. The maximum power densities were 3.9, 5.7, 9.4 and 2.8 mW·cm−2 for Ce/Mn molar ratios of 1:3, 1:5, 1:10 and 1:15, respectively. When Ce/Mn molar ratio was 1:10, the performance of CeO2-QDs@MnO2-based DMFC reached the highest point. The polarization and power density curves for MnO2@CeO2-QDs-based passive DMFCs were shown in Fig. 7b and the highest power density was also obtained at the Ce/Mn molar ratio of 1:10. Therefore, both CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs were applied with Ce/Mn molar ratio of 1:10. Fig. 7c illustrated the performance of CeO2-QDs@MnO2, MnO2@CeO2-QDs, MnO2 and CeO2-QDs-based passive DMFCs, and the maximum power densities were 9.4, 7.8, 5.6 and 2.0 mW·cm−2, respectively. The electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) reflected the electron conductivity and ion diffusion of the composite catalysts. The Nyquist plots for CeO2, MnO2, CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs were shown in Fig. 7d, which were consisted of a high frequency semicircle part and a low frequency straight part. In the corresponding equivalent electrical circuit, RΩ, Rct, Rmt and constant phase angle element (CPE) represented the total ohmic resistance, charge transfer resistance, mass transfer resistance and realistic reaction conditions, respectively [40,41]. The fitting results showed that Rct for CeO2-QDs@MnO2, MnO2@CeO2-QDs, MnO2 and CeO2 were 2.45, 3.25, 4.27 and 6.60 Ω m−2, respectively. The heterogeneous interfaces and oxygen vacancies in CeO2-QDs@MnO2 composites could improve the electrical conductivity. Rmt for CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs were 8.87 and 11.74 Ω cm−2, respectively. This result confirmed CeO2-QDs existed in the interior of MnO2 can accelerate the mass transfer. The performance of air-breathing DMFCs and the passive DMFCs were presented in Fig. 8a. The maximum power densities of CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs-based air-breathing DMFCs were 8.5 and 7.0 mW·cm−2, respectively. The passive DMFCs were 9.4 and 7.8 mW·cm−2, slightly higher than that of the air-breathing DMFCs. The maximum power densities of Pt/C DMFCs was 7.66 mW·cm−2. Stability is another main factor to evaluate the cell performance. As shown in Fig. 8b, the stability tests for CeO2-QDs@MnO2, CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and Pt/C-based air-breathing DMFCs under 10 mA·cm−2 constant current densities were monitored. Within the 1300 h test, CeO2-QDs@MnO2-based air-breathing DMFC showed higher out-put voltages than that of MnO2@CeO2-QDs and Pt/C. Table S2 listed the data in earlier published papers. Compared with the literature, the maximum power density of CeO2-QDs@MnO2-based passive DMFC didn’t show a significant improvement at 20 °C. However, an extremely excellent stability was presented for CeO2-QDs@MnO2 catalyst. In order to explore the short-term stability of DMFCs under different current densities, Fig. 8c showed the voltage variations at 10, 20, 30 and 50 mA·cm−2 in the passive DMFCs. The fuel solution was refreshed and the data were recorded every 10 h. When the current densities was 10 mA·cm−2, both CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and CeO2-QDs@MnO2-based DMFCs were relatively stable. However, with the current density increased, the cell voltage of CeO2-QDs@MnO2-based DMFCs were still stable, while the stability of MnO2@CeO2-QDs-based DMFCs gradually decreased at high current density. In both CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs catalysts, CeO2 showed effective oxygen adsorption capacity and acted as oxygen storage and transfer reactor. As shown in Fig. 9, CeO2 could store oxygen under well-oxygenated conditions at low current density; and then the adsorptive oxygen would transfer to reactive oxygen species through Ce4+/Ce3+ redox couple. When MnO2 was starved of oxygen at high current density, the reactive oxygen species came from CeO2 could be timely transferred to surrounding catalytic active sites. Consequently, the temporary storage and timely replenishment mechanism for oxygen could significantly enhance the ORR efficiency at cathode. Due to the CeO2-QDs was coated on MnO2 in MnO2 @CeO2-QDs catalyst, the effective three phase reaction surface on MnO2 was inevitably hindered by CeO2. Therefore, CeO2-QDs@MnO2 catalysts indicated the superior ORR activity and stability in the high discharge currents especially for air-breathing passive DMFC. 4 Conclusions In this study, MnO2 supported on CeO2-QDs (CeO2-QDs@MnO2) and CeO2-QDs supported on MnO2 (MnO2@CeO2-QDs) composite with different loading method were synthesized to explore the role of CeO2 on the ORR activity. CV and LSV results illustrated that CeO2-QDs@MnO2 showed the superior intrinsic catalytic activity than MnO2@CeO2-QDs. And then CeO2-QDs@MnO2 or MnO2@CeO2-QDs were used as the cathode catalyst, PtRu/C as the anode catalyst to assemble the passive DMFC. The maximum power densities of CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2 @CeO2-QDs-based passive DMFCs were 9.4 and 7.8 mW·cm−2, while 8.5 and 7.0 mW·cm−2 for air-breathing DMFCs, respectively. Moreover, within the 1300 h stability test, CeO2-QDs@MnO2-based air-breathing DMFC showed higher out-put voltages than that of MnO2@CeO2-QDs and Pt/C. CeO2-QDs@MnO2 also presented an excellent stability especially for the high current density. This result confirmed that CeO2-QDs acted as oxygen storage and transfer reactor to accelerate the mass transfer. The distribution of CeO2-QDs would significantly affect the ORR activity at cathode. This work developed a new thought about the loading method of CeO2 on the ORR catalytic activity for CeO2/MnO2 heterostructured catalysts. coredata.dc:description: The oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) efficiency of direct methanol fuel cell (DMFC) is of great significance. In this work, MnO2 supported on CeO2-QDs (CeO2-QDs@MnO2) and CeO2-QDs supported on MnO2 (MnO2@CeO2-QDs) composite with different loading method were synthesized to investigate the role of CeO2 for ORR, according to the excellent oxygen adsorption and oxygen ion conductivity of CeO2 quantum dots (CeO2-QDs). A passive DMFC was assembled by CeO2-QDs@MnO2 or MnO2@CeO2-QDs as cathodic catalyst and PtRu/C as anodic catalyst. The maximum power densities for CeO2-QDs@MnO2 and MnO2@CeO2-QDs-based DMFCs were 9.4 and 7.8 mW·cm−2, while 8.5 and 7.0 mW·cm−2 for air-breathing DMFCs, respectively. CeO2-QDs@MnO2 showed a more superior ORR activity and stability in the high discharge currents especially for air-breathing DMFCs. The temporary storage and timely replenishment mechanism of oxygen in CeO2-QDs@MnO2 catalyst could significantly enhance the ORR efficiency at cathode. This work developed a new thought about the loading method of CeO2 on the ORR catalytic activity for CeO2/MnO2 catalysts.
coredata.dc:title: Evolution of oxygen reduction property by the role of CeO2 in CeO2/MnO2 cathode catalyst for passive direct methanol fuel cells
